{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}} {{Infobox tennis biography | name = Hakon Leffler | image = Hakon Leffler 1937.JPG | alt = | caption = Hakon Leffler in 1937 | fullname = | residence = | birth_date = {{birth date|1887|3|11|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Gothenburg]], [[Sweden]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1972|7|31|1887|3|11|df=yes}} | death_place = Gothenburg, Sweden | height = | weight = | college = | turnedpro = | retired = | plays = | careerprizemoney = | tennishofyear = | tennishofid = | website = }}
'''Hakon Leffler''' (11 March 1887 – 31 July 1972) was a Swedish engineer, businessman and [[tennis]] player.
He was the son of merchant [[Carl Leopold Leffler]], studied [[electrical engineering]] at the [[Royal Institute of Technology]] from 1905 to 1908, and at [[Uppsala University]] where he graduated in 1910.<ref>[http://runeberg.org/vemarvem/gota48/0577.html Vem är Vem?: Götalandsdelen utom Skåne (1948), p. 577]</ref> After having worked at the M.E. Delbanco company 1912-1915, he became the CEO of Svensk oljeslageri AB 1916. In 1929 he became the deputy CEO at [[Gamlestadens fabriker]], a textile company in Gothenburg, and in 1935 its CEO.
==Olympic career== Leffler competed in two individual tennis events at the [[1912 Summer Olympics]].<ref name="sports-reference">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/le/hakon-leffler-1.html |title=Hakon Leffler |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=sok>[http://sok.se/idrottare/idrottare/h/hakon-leffler.html Hakon Leffler]. Swedish Olympic Committee</ref>
