{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}
The '''Perth Metropolitan Markets''' were a fruit and vegetable wholesale markets located at 840 (Lots 500-504) [[Wellington Street, Perth|Wellington Street]] in [[West Perth, Western Australia|West Perth]] from 1929 to 1989, when they moved to their current site in [[Canning Vale, Western Australia|Canning Vale]].<ref>[http://www.perthmarket.com.au/historicalphotogallery.php?PageNumber=7 Perth Market City Historical Photo Gallery]</ref>

The markets were originally established at [[Roe Street, Perth]], at the western end of the railway station (regularly referred to as the "Old Markets"),<ref>{{Citation | author1=Roberts, L. S | author2=Western Australia. Audit Dept | title=Metropolitan Markets : a history of events leading to the formation of a central public market in Perth, Western Australia | publication-date=1973 | publisher=Audit Dept | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/159322442 | accessdate=5 March 2017 }}</ref><ref>For instance - the report - {{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article211010124 |title=Metropolitan Markets |newspaper=[[Gnowangerup Times]] |volume=1, |issue=15 |location=Western Australia |date=25 January 1913 |accessdate=5 March 2017 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}} is referring to the old 'Metropolitan Market' at the railway station</ref> with a more comprehensive market constructed on a 111-acre site, bounded by Wellington, Sutherland and Market Streets by the Metropolitan Market Trust.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article58336838?search |title=Metropolitan Market Trust|publisher=[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|The Sunday Times]]|date=23 October 1927|page=11|accessdate=2 November 2011}}</ref> The Trust was established by the Government in September 1927.  The Wellington Street Markets were formally opened on 14 June 1929 by the Deputy Premier of Western Australia, [[John Willcock]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32287199 |title=Metropolitan Markets|newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth, WA |date=13 June 1929 |accessdate=10 July 2012 |page=16 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32287503 |title=New Markets |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth, WA |date=14 June 1929 |accessdate=10 July 2012 |page=22 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38886479 |title=Metropolitan Markets|newspaper=[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail]] |location=Perth, WA |date=20 June 1929 |accessdate=10 July 2012 |page=45 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=HRRC | title=Opening of the Metropolitan Markets, West Perth, Friday 14 June 1929 | publication-date=1929 | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/8740423 | accessdate=5 March 2017 }}</ref> The site incorporated an auctioneering area (72,750 sq ft), meat markets (2,400 sq ft) and egg and poultry markets (9,900 sq ft).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32215942 |title=Metropolitan Markets |newspaper=[[The West Australian]]|location=Perth, WA |date=16 August 1928 |accessdate=10 July 2012 |page=18 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The site also included a public restaurant, post office and several bank branch offices.

By the 1950s protective restrictions on road transport by the Road Transport Regulation Board were being lightened, and more trucking of produce into and away from the markets was beginning to have effect on Wellington Street.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Western Australia. Transport Board | title=State Transportation Co-ordination Act 1933-1954 : notes for general information | publication-date=1956 | publisher=Paterson Brokensha | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/159323979 | accessdate=5 March 2017 }}</ref>

The closing down of various freight services on the [[Western Australian Government Railways]] system as it was changed to a bulk freight operation, and its new brand and style of operation,<ref>{{Citation | author1=Affleck, Fred N | author2=Clark, Bill | author3=Western Australian Government Railways Commission | author4=Affleck, Fred | title=On track : the making of Westrail, 1950 to 1976 | publication-date=1978 | publisher=Department of Conservation & the Environment, West | isbn=978-0-7244-7560-5 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Dyson, D. J | author2=Ellis, R. J | author3=Western Australia. Transport Board. Economic Research Section | title=Report on motor truck operating costs : report prepared by the Economics Research Section of the W.A. Transport Board | publication-date=1961 | publisher=W.A. Transport Board | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/157610406 | accessdate=5 March 2017 }}</ref> saw the location of the markets and proximity to the [[central business district]] and the high land values as a problem.

Various reviews and changes to processes at the markets were occurring prior to the closure.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Longson, Ian | author2=Deukett, Marion | author3=Western Australia. Marketing and Economics Branch | title=A review of fruit and vegetable market reporting at the Perth metropolitan markets | publication-date=1981 | publisher=Western Australian Dept. of Agriculture, Marketing and Economics Branch | isbn=978-0-7244-9357-9 }}</ref>

In 1990, the Metropolitan Market Trust changed its name to the Perth Market Authority and in 1989 the Authority relocated the markets to a site in Canning Vale.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Rogers, Steve | author2=Metropolitan Market Trust (W.A.) | title=The Metropolitan markets : the heartbeat of Perth, 1929-1989 | publication-date=1989 | publisher=Metropolitan Market Trust | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/13854827 | accessdate=5 March 2017 }}</ref>

The original market site has since been redeveloped and is the site of Watertown Brand Outlet Centre<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watertownbrandoutlet.com.au/Information/Getting%20Here|title=Getting here|publisher=Watertown Brand Outlet Centre|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> and the offices of the [[Royal Automobile Club of Western Australia]].

